# CaptionDB AI Pipeline Engineering Contract

## Purpose

This document defines the architecture and implementation rules for the AI pipeline.

The AI pipeline is responsible for transforming an input video into high-quality captions while remaining modular, observable, configurable, and production-ready.

The AI pipeline must never become tightly coupled to a specific model, provider, OCR engine, or scene detection implementation.

---

# Engineering Philosophy

The AI pipeline must be:

- Modular
- Deterministic where appropriate
- Configurable
- Observable
- Fault tolerant
- Provider independent
- Easy to benchmark
- Easy to replace

The pipeline should be viewed as an orchestration system rather than a single script.

---

# Pipeline Overview

Every video should pass through the following stages.

Video Input

↓

Validation

↓

Metadata Extraction

↓

Scene Detection

↓

Frame Sampling

↓

OCR (Optional)

↓

Visual Understanding

↓

Context Builder

↓

Prompt Generation

↓

Caption Generation

↓

Quality Evaluation

↓

Post Processing

↓

Export

Each stage is independent.

---

# Pipeline Orchestrator

The pipeline must be coordinated by a PipelineOrchestrator.

Responsibilities:

- execute stages
- collect outputs
- handle failures
- collect metrics
- emit events
- manage retries

No individual service should control pipeline execution.

---

# Stage Isolation

Each stage should receive structured input and return structured output.

Stages must not modify unrelated pipeline state.

Avoid hidden side effects.

---

# Service Responsibilities

Each major capability must exist as its own service.

Examples:

VideoService

SceneDetectionService

FrameSamplingService

OCRService

VisionService

PromptService

CaptionService

JudgeService

MemoryService

ExportService

MetricsService

---

# Plugin Architecture

Every AI component must be replaceable.

Examples:

SceneDetector

OCR Engine

LLM Provider

Embedding Provider

Judge

Exporter

Future replacements should require minimal code changes.

---

# Configuration

Pipeline behaviour must be configuration driven.

Never hardcode:

Frame count

Confidence thresholds

Temperatures

Prompt versions

Retry limits

Model names

Timeouts

Chunk sizes

Cache settings

---

# Video Validation

Validate:

Video format

Duration

Resolution

Frame rate

File size

Reject unsupported videos before processing.

---

# Scene Detection

Scene detection should remain abstract.

Never hardcode a specific implementation.

Allow future replacement without changing pipeline code.

Scene detector should return:

Scene ID

Start Time

End Time

Confidence

Metadata

---

# Frame Sampling

Sampling strategy must be configurable.

Support future strategies.

Examples:

Uniform

Adaptive

Keyframe

Motion-aware

Never assume a fixed number of frames.

---

# OCR

OCR is optional.

Pipeline must continue if OCR is disabled.

OCR output should be normalized.

Never tightly couple downstream stages to a specific OCR engine.

---

# Visual Understanding

Visual analysis should receive:

Frames

Scene metadata

OCR output

Context

Return structured scene understanding.

Avoid returning raw text whenever possible.

---

# Prompt Generation

Prompt generation belongs inside PromptService.

Prompt text must never be hardcoded inside business logic.

Prompt templates should be versioned.

Support multiple prompt versions.

---

# Caption Generation

Caption generation should support multiple styles.

Current styles:

Formal

Sarcastic

Humorous-Tech

Humorous-NonTech

Adding another style should require configuration only.

---

# Candidate Generation

Support multiple candidate captions.

Candidate count should be configurable.

Do not hardcode the number of candidates.

---

# Quality Evaluation

Quality evaluation should be independent.

Judge should evaluate:

Relevance

Accuracy

Style consistency

Grammar

Safety

Completeness

Judge should not generate captions.

Judge only evaluates.

---

# Memory

Memory should remain optional.

Memory stores contextual information between scenes.

Examples:

Characters

Objects

Locations

Previous actions

Memory should improve consistency.

Pipeline must function without memory enabled.

---

# Context Builder

Context Builder merges:

Scene information

OCR

Memory

Metadata

Prompt configuration

Return structured context.

Never concatenate strings throughout the application.

---

# Fireworks Independence

The pipeline must never directly call Fireworks.

Only FireworksClient may communicate with Fireworks.

Pipeline depends on interfaces.

---

# Retry Policy

Retry only transient failures.

Examples:

Timeout

Temporary service unavailable

Rate limit

Do not retry:

Validation errors

Configuration errors

Invalid input

---

# Timeouts

Every AI request must have configurable timeout values.

Never wait indefinitely.

---

# Metrics

Collect metrics for every stage.

Minimum metrics:

Start time

End time

Duration

Success

Failure

Retry count

Memory usage

API latency

Token usage

---

# Logging

Every stage logs:

Started

Completed

Duration

Warnings

Failures

Retries

Never log prompts containing sensitive data.

Never log API keys.

---

# Caching

Cache only expensive computations.

Examples:

Scene detection

OCR

Embeddings

Vision descriptions

Prompt templates

Cache must be configurable.

---

# Error Recovery

If one stage fails:

Determine whether recovery is possible.

Continue processing whenever safe.

Avoid failing the entire pipeline because of one recoverable error.

---

# Parallel Processing

Independent scenes may process concurrently.

Shared state must remain thread-safe.

Avoid race conditions.

Do not parallelize operations that depend on sequential context.

---

# Structured Data

Every stage exchanges typed models.

Never pass anonymous dictionaries between stages.

Prefer Pydantic models or dataclasses.

---

# Extensibility

Future additions should require minimal modification.

Examples:

Audio transcription

Object detection

Face recognition

Embeddings

Translation

Subtitle generation

Support future pipeline stages.

---

# Prompt Versioning

Prompt templates should support versioning.

Example:

v1

v2

v3

Never overwrite previous prompt versions.

---

# Feature Flags

Support enabling or disabling:

OCR

Memory

Judge

Candidate Generation

Caching

Experimental prompts

Configuration controls features.

Never comment out code to disable functionality.

---

# AI Provider Independence

The application should not depend on Fireworks.

Support future providers.

Examples:

OpenAI

Anthropic

Local models

AMD optimized deployments

Only provider adapters should change.

---

# Testing

Each stage must support isolated testing.

Mock external providers.

Avoid real API calls during unit tests.

Integration tests should verify complete pipeline behaviour.

---

# Documentation

Every pipeline stage should document:

Purpose

Input

Output

Dependencies

Failure modes

Configuration

---

# Self Review Checklist

Before completing implementation verify:

✓ Stage has one responsibility

✓ Configuration driven

✓ Typed models

✓ Replaceable implementation

✓ Proper logging

✓ Metrics collected

✓ Retry strategy

✓ Timeout configured

✓ Structured outputs

✓ No hardcoded values

✓ Documentation updated

✓ Tests added

✓ Compatible with architecture contract

If any check fails, revise implementation before completion.

---

End of AI Pipeline Engineering Contract.
